article.description: Freddie Owens scored a career-high 24 points and No. 15 Wisconsin overcame shooting struggles to beat Eastern Illinois 81-47 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Badgers just 38 percent from floor
article.linkText: No. 15 Wisconsin overcomes shooting to win
article.story: MADISON, Wis. (AP) --Freddie Owens' shots have been falling so far this season. He thinks it's only a matter of time before his teammates find their shooting touch as well. Owens scored a career-high 24 points Tuesday as No. 15 Wisconsin extended its home winning streak to 14 games with an 81-47 victory over Eastern Illinois. Owens made all four of his 3-point tries and finished 7-of-8 from the floor for the Badgers (2-0), who shot below 40 percent for the second straight game. Wisconsin shot just 38 percent as a team and the rest of the Badgers besides Owens were a combined 14-of-41. "You have games where you shoot well as a team and you have games where you don't," said Owens, shooting 80 percent (12 of 15) through two games. "We're doing other things besides worrying about our field-goal percentage." The Badgers are doing everything else pretty well. They got to the free throw line 41 times against Eastern Illinois (0-2), making 34. And Wisconsin committed just seven turnovers while forcing 23 by the Panthers. Wisconsin coach Bo Ryan said he was particularly impressed with his team's work on the defensive end. "Well, that end of the floor is always about work and attitude and discipline," said Ryan, who added that he isn't concerned with his team's shooting struggles. "There's no sharp shooting on the defensive end. Guts and hard work and attitude and sticking to the rules of our defense always gives you a chance." Jason Wright scored 11 points to lead Eastern Illinois, which committed 29 fouls to Wisconsin's 15. Eastern Illinois led 18-17 in the first half, but was held to just two field goals in a stretch of over 12 minutes that extended into the second half. The Badgers used a 26-8 run during the stretch to take control of the game. "They're really a solid defensive team," Eastern Illinois coach Rick Samuels said of Wisconsin, which limited the Panthers to 38.6 percent shooting. "They're physical and strong. We couldn't get anything going in the second half, and that's just because they wore us out." Among the players in foul trouble for Eastern Illinois was Derik Hollyfield, who fouled out with just one point in 11 minutes. Hollyfield scored a team-high 27 points in the Panthers' season opener against Northern Illinois. Wisconsin got 15 points from Devin Harris and 12 from Mike Wilkinson. Harris was 11 of 14 from the free throw line but just two of 11 from the floor. The cold night by Harris and the rest of the Badgers didn't matter, however, because Owens picked up the slack. When Eastern Illinois went to a zone defense in the second half, Owens responded by making three straight 3-pointers to push Wisconsin's lead to 74-45. "I was feeling pretty good," said Owens, whose previous career high was 23 points against Temple in 2001. "I was fortunate to get some open looks." And the Badgers were fortunate Owens took advantage of being open.
